---
description: Project standards for stack, security, and environment handling
alwaysApply: true
---

# Project Context

- Build with Next.js.
- Use Material UI for UI components.
- Use SCSS Modules for component/page styling.
- Use Prisma for database access and schema management.
- Sanity is optional and should only be added when content modeling requires a CMS.

# Security and Secrets

- Treat this repository as public; never commit secrets.
- Never hardcode API keys, tokens, credentials, or private URLs in code.
- Put all sensitive values in environment variables and document them in `.env.example`.
- Do not write real values into `.env` files; only the user should set local secret values.
- If adding a new integration, add/update corresponding env variable placeholders in `.env.example`.

# Implementation Preferences

- Prefer server-side secret usage; expose values to client only when they are intentionally public (`NEXT_PUBLIC_*`).
- Keep code modular by feature (tool modules/pages/components/services).
- For Next.js + MUI, prefer theme-driven styles and use SCSS Modules where custom styling is needed.
- For Prisma, keep schema changes tracked with migrations and update generated client usage accordingly.

# Delivery Requirements

- When implementing features, include a short note of any new required environment variables.
- If Sanity is introduced, include setup steps and required env vars in docs and `.env.example`.
